  "prompt": "How does modern Greek language differ from ancient Greek?",
  "response": "Modern Greek and Ancient Greek differ in various ways, covering aspects of phonology, vocabulary, grammar, and usage. Here are some of the key differences:\n\n1. **Phonology (Pronunciation):**\n   - Ancient Greek had a more complex system of vowel lengths and diphthongs, while Modern Greek has simplified these.\n   - Ancient Greek had a pitch accent system, whereas Modern Greek uses a stress accent.\n   - Certain consonants have changed in pronunciation. For instance, Ancient Greek \"\u03b2\" (beta) was pronounced as 'b', but in Modern Greek, it is pronounced 'v'.\n\n2. **Vocabulary:**\n   - While there is a continuity in many words, numerous words have either fallen out of use or evolved in meaning.\n   - Modern Greek has borrowed extensively from other languages, particularly Turkish, Italian, French, and English.\n\n3. **Grammar:**\n   - Ancient Greek had a more complex case system (five cases: nominative, genitive, dative, accusative, vocative). Modern Greek has simplified this to four cases (nominative, genitive, accusative, vocative), and the dative case is mostly obsolete.\n   - Verb conjugations have evolved, with some ancient forms disappearing and new forms emerging in Modern Greek.\n\n4. **Syntax:**\n   - Sentence structure in Modern Greek tends to be less rigid, with word order being more flexible due to reliance on prepositions and other constructs.\n\n5. **Writing System:**\n   - The alphabet used is largely the same, but there have been changes in pronunciation and the use of certain characters.\n   - Modern Greek has simplified the use of diacritics (accents and breathings) compared to Ancient Greek.\n\n6. **Function Words:**\n   - Pronouns, conjunctions, and particles have evolved in both form and usage.\n\n7. **Forms of Greek:**\n   - Koine Greek emerged as a common dialect during the Hellenistic and Roman periods, transitioning towards the Medieval Greek that later led into Modern Greek.\n\nUnderstanding these differences takes into account the linguistic evolution over millennia, influenced by historical, social, and cultural changes.",
